INSERT INTO `advisoryitems` (`ID`, `HeaderColLeft`, `HeaderColRight`, `ContentColRight`, `SmallContent`, `FooterColLeft`, `FooterColRight`, `ContentColLeftID`) VALUES
(6, '<p>brand &amp; concept strategies</p>', '<p>Dag Landewall</p>', '<h1>get some character</h1>\n<p>It is no coincidence that many of the world''s most successful brands have a founder with a strong personality who also becomes the company''s brand personality. IKEA is Ingvar Kamprad and Apple is (still) Steve Jobs. But that does not mean companies without a charismatic founder cannot develop a strong, relevant and likeble character. Every single company has its own history with its unique traits that add up to the company''s personality.</p>\n<p>I believe that a brand first of all should be authentic and true to its own culture. Instead of trying to become what you are not - be clear about what you really are. Identify your virtues and be true to them. Then your brand acquires authenticity and character, which is paramount for creating an emotional and lasting connection between your brand and the consumers.</p>', '<p>Dag Landewall, Senior Brand Strategist, is the co-founder of Reactor and has over 30 years of retail and concept development experience. He leads the company''s brand strategy work and creates compelling, consumer-relevant and to-the-point brand stories and personalities for select corporate clients.</p>', '<p>(+47) 952 12 345</p>', '<p><a href="mailto:dag@reactorretail.com">dag@reactorretail.com</a></p>', 257),
(51, '<p>retail design</p>', '<p>stein eirik berg</p>', '<h1>passion driven</h1>\n<h2>shopping experiences</h2>\n<p>The perfect store, an artistic vision, the ultimate design, filled with dreams to inspire, incite and entertain. But a beautiful shopping experience is not enough. For a store to be successful, its retail design must express the soul of the brand - i.e. the brand´s values and strength. Striking the right balance between the products, communication, design, architecture and education is the only way to achieve this goal. As a retail designer, you need a unique mix of elements for each project, because every brand develops differently.</p>\n<p>The ultimate shopping experience is a place driven by passion and experience. You can have a fantastically designed store, but if the owners and staff are not fully behind it, it will never work. Fantastic opportunities exist for imaginative retailers.</p>', '<p>Stein Berg is a highly skilled retail designer and store planner with more than 30 years of retail and concept development experience, and with hundred of thousands of square meters of retail space planned and behind the retail experience of Stokke, IKEA, Oslo Airport, Moods of Norway and many more. </p>', '<p>(+47) 917 58 805</p>', '<p>seb@reactorretail.com</p>', 261),
(52, '<p>concept &amp; design direction</p>', '<p>øyvind nystad</p>', '<h1>natural instinct</h1>\n<h2>is king in store design</h2>\n<p>Far too many people place an equals sign between the store experience and design. For us, design is a part of many things that must be defined when one creates a successful store concept. What primarily builds a concept – and hence the experience of a store, is the product line – how it is divided up and presented. The other dimension lies in how one affects and controls a gait pattern – by working with glance directions and rhythms in the room. We are of course equipped with many primal instincts, which serve mainly to identify sense-related similarities and differences in our surroundings. Sense perceptions such as light, smell and sound also belong to this dimension. All the elements contribute to dramatizing the customer''s  perception of your shop and your brand name.</p>', '<p>Øyvind Nystad, Creative Director and co-founder of Reactor. More than 25 years of concept development and design work for some of the world''s most respected brands has made Øyvind one of the most respected retail designers in Europe. </p>', '<p>(+47) 911 78 924</p>', '<p>oyvind@rectorretail.com</p>', 327),
(78, '<p>brand idenity design</p>', '<p>hilde steen aamodt</p>', '<h1>gold diggers</h1>\n<p>Excellent visual expressions of brands are mostly based on the company''s own DNA and are able to tell the history, aspirations and vision of the brand in a condensed form. I believe in cultivating the client company''s personal traits, characteristics and values to its full potential and prefer creating the identity from within, based on visual translations of strategic insights rather than to base it on design trends. My experience is that this approach results in extended longevity for the brand and that it also generates greater pride and internal ownership. In addition, idenitites created from within are often perceived as more unique and trustworthy in the marketplace. Consequently, our approach is that every company and brand possesses gold ore waiting to be discovered - and our job is to find that ore and make sustainable brandwork out of it.</p>', '<p>Hilde Steen Aamodt, Senior Graphic Designer, is a highly experienced graphic designer. In addition to creating commercially successful identities, she creates complete design programs and guidelines, brand &amp; in-store communication, editorial design and advertising. Hilde is behind the visual expression for a wide range of brand designs i.e. Nille, Jøtul, Match, Voice, Regatta, Printz, Lefdal, Eurosko, Gyldendal, Tiden and Miles. Her work has been awarded The Award for Design Excellence.</p>', '<p>(+47) 900 39 019</p>', '<p>hilde@reactorretail.com</p>', 260),
(79, '<p>brand marketing</p>', '<p>inger guttormsen </p>', '<h1>category captains </h1>\n<p>The huge rise of private labels has fundamentally changed market power in recent years, from big brands towards retailers private labels. However, very few retailer private labels have the brand power to shoulder the role of being a category captain. And without a strong category captain brand, it is difficult for a retailer to become a preferred category destination. A soft drink department without Coke or a barbecue department without Weber does not resonate well with consumers. Wise retailers thus know that they need strong brands to build category authority. So if you own a good industry brand, take a broader view on how you can help retailers transform categories into destinations, creating interesting and inspiring shopping experences that also make customers connect emotionally with your brand and your products. This lets you create a true win-win relationship for both the retailer and your brand.</p>', '<p>Inger Guttormsen joined Reactor in 2012 and is the latest expert to join our advisory team. She has over 10 years of professional experience, ranging from building strong brands through marketing positions at L''Oréal, to managing the Nike retail brand strategy and implementation within the Norwegian sport industry. Inger is advicing select brand clients on how to create strong instore</p>\n<p>brand presentations that resonate well among retailers and consumers while meeting the brand''s strategic objectives.</p>', '<p>(+ 47) 924 91 600</p>', '<p>inger@reactorretail.com</p>', 263),
(80, '<p>retail tender management &amp; roll-outs</p>', '<p>erik huseby</p>', '<h1>big ideas </h1>\n<h2>into the real world</h2>\n<p>In the disruptive and unpredictable market of today, many great ideas become irrelevant before they reach the marketplace. For many large companies it has proved difficult to adjust their concept development and implementation processes to this new reality.</p>\n<p>However, my experience is that it is possible to shorten the interval between the creation of the next big thing and its first encounter with real customers.</p>\n<p>Our approach is to prepare a concept for roll-out right from the start.  Also, concept elements should be prototyped as they are developed at the drawing table. Finally, a successful procurement process requires in-depth knowledge of the shop-fitting market and production methods. A professionally done retail tender management process normally accounts for 20 - 30% investment savings. Talk to me, and I will tell you how.</p>', '<p>Erik Huseby, Managing Director of Reactor Products, our implementation arm, leads our work with bringing the concepts we create into the real world, through sourcing, piloting and roll-out management. Erik has over 20 years of expertise in his field and is a leading shop-fitting authority and manages tender and hardware sourcing processes for a large number of our clients.   </p>', '<p>(+47) 916 86 244</p>', '<p>erik@reactorretail.com</p>', 264),
(83, '<p>retail art direction</p>', '<p>ann-catrin friborg</p>', '<h1>mind the details </h1>\n<p>Occasionally one feels welcomed just by entering a store or a restaurant. At first, it can be hard to understand why, but after a while you realize that somebody, out of many details, has created an inspiring, exciting and holistic customer journey and shopping experience. With inspiration from the world around us, we create and visualize conceptual ideas to convey the concepts overarching the design ideas and emotional expressions that make customers emotionally connect with your concept and brand. This is our tool for creating a common vision and understanding of the strategic design and conceptual direction of the concept. The result is a concept where products, surfaces, graphics and other esthetics work together to create a specific, successful retail business, hopefully answering the most important question for anyone in retail: why should anyone come to my store?</p>', '<p>Ann-Catrin Friborg, Retail Art Director, joined Reactor in 2003 after a 14-year international store design career with IKEA.</p>\n<p>She is an expert in visualizing conceptual environments and shopping experiences, and has led several major concept development projects, directing the creation of strong, differentiating and coherent retail experiences. </p>', '<p>(+47)  97 68 38 52 </p>', '<p>ancf@reactorretail.com</p>', 258);
INSERT INTO `advisoryitems_live` (`ID`, `HeaderColLeft`, `HeaderColRight`, `ContentColRight`, `SmallContent`, `FooterColLeft`, `FooterColRight`, `ContentColLeftID`) VALUES
(6, '<p>brand &amp; concept strategies</p>', '<p>Dag Landewall</p>', '<h1>get some character</h1>\n<p>It is no coincidence that many of the world''s most successful brands have a founder with a strong personality who also becomes the company''s brand personality. IKEA is Ingvar Kamprad and Apple is (still) Steve Jobs. But that does not mean companies without a charismatic founder cannot develop a strong, relevant and likeble character. Every single company has its own history with its unique traits that add up to the company''s personality.</p>\n<p>I believe that a brand first of all should be authentic and true to its own culture. Instead of trying to become what you are not - be clear about what you really are. Identify your virtues and be true to them. Then your brand acquires authenticity and character, which is paramount for creating an emotional and lasting connection between your brand and the consumers.</p>', '<p>Dag Landewall, Senior Brand Strategist, is the co-founder of Reactor and has over 30 years of retail and concept development experience. He leads the company''s brand strategy work and creates compelling, consumer-relevant and to-the-point brand stories and personalities for select corporate clients.</p>', '<p>(+47) 952 12 345</p>', '<p><a href="mailto:dag@reactorretail.com">dag@reactorretail.com</a></p>', 257),
(51, '<p>retail design</p>', '<p>stein eirik berg</p>', '<h1>passion driven</h1>\n<h2>shopping experiences</h2>\n<p>The perfect store, an artistic vision, the ultimate design, filled with dreams to inspire, incite and entertain. But a beautiful shopping experience is not enough. For a store to be successful, its retail design must express the soul of the brand - i.e. the brand´s values and strength. Striking the right balance between the products, communication, design, architecture and education is the only way to achieve this goal. As a retail designer, you need a unique mix of elements for each project, because every brand develops differently.</p>\n<p>The ultimate shopping experience is a place driven by passion and experience. You can have a fantastically designed store, but if the owners and staff are not fully behind it, it will never work. Fantastic opportunities exist for imaginative retailers.</p>', '<p>Stein Berg is a highly skilled retail designer and store planner with more than 30 years of retail and concept development experience, and with hundred of thousands of square meters of retail space planned and behind the retail experience of Stokke, IKEA, Oslo Airport, Moods of Norway and many more. </p>', '<p>(+47) 917 58 805</p>', '<p>seb@reactorretail.com</p>', 261),
(52, '<p>concept &amp; design direction</p>', '<p>øyvind nystad</p>', '<h1>natural instinct</h1>\n<h2>is king in store design</h2>\n<p>Far too many people place an equals sign between the store experience and design. For us, design is a part of many things that must be defined when one creates a successful store concept. What primarily builds a concept – and hence the experience of a store, is the product line – how it is divided up and presented. The other dimension lies in how one affects and controls a gait pattern – by working with glance directions and rhythms in the room. We are of course equipped with many primal instincts, which serve mainly to identify sense-related similarities and differences in our surroundings. Sense perceptions such as light, smell and sound also belong to this dimension. All the elements contribute to dramatizing the customer''s  perception of your shop and your brand name.</p>', '<p>Øyvind Nystad, Creative Director and co-founder of Reactor. More than 25 years of concept development and design work for some of the world''s most respected brands has made Øyvind one of the most respected retail designers in Europe. </p>', '<p>(+47) 911 78 924</p>', '<p>oyvind@rectorretail.com</p>', 327),
