(207, 6, 76, '<p>brand &amp; concept strategies</p>', '<p>dag landewall</p>', '<h1>from vice to virtue</h1>\n<h2>a brand needs character</h2>\n<p>It''s not a coincidence that many of the worlds most successful brands has a founder with a strong personality that also becomes the company''s brand personality. IKEA is Ingvar Kamprad and Apple is (still) Steve Jobs. But that doesn''t mean companies without a charismatic founder cannot develop a strong, relevant and likeble character. Every single company has it''s own history with it''s unique traits, and ways of acting which add''s up to the company''s personality. We believe that a brand first of all should be authentic an true to it''s own culture. Instead of trying to become what you''re not - be clear about what you really are. Identify and describe your virtues and define the consequences of being true to them. Do that and your brand get authenticity and character. Then use it as a foundation for your concept development and design work.</p>', '<p>Dag Landewall, senior brand strategist, is the co-founder of Reactor and has over 30 years of retail and concept development experience. He’s leading the company''s brand strategy work and creates compelling, consumer relevant and to-the-point brand stories and personalities for select corporate clients.</p>', '<p>+47 952 12 345</p>', '<p><a href="mailto:dag@reactorretail.com">dag@reactorretail.com</a></p>', 257),
(208, 52, 24, '<p>concept &amp; design direction</p>', '<p>øyvind nystad</p>', '<h1>natural instinct</h1>\n<h2>is king in store design</h2>\n<p>Too many view design as the actual shopping experience. To us, design is just one of the dimensions needed to create a successful retail concept. The first dimension is, of course, the product range and how it''s directed, segmented and presented to your customers. The second dimension is how interesting you can make the customers journey through your store, creating interesting sight lines and by changing the rhythm in different areas of the store. Why all this is important? As humans, we automatically try to understand and to navigate in a new environment. We use our natural instincts and all our senses to identify differences and to detect potential opportunities and dangers in our environment. Therefore, creating a sensory shopping experience including light, sound, shapes and scents helps to dramatise and build your customer''s perception of your store and your brand.</p>', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Øyvind Nystad, creative director and co-founder of Reactor. More than 25 years of concept development and design work for some of the worlds most respected brands has made Øyvind one of the most respected retail designers in Europe. </p>', '<p>+47 911 78 924</p>', '<p>oyvind@rectorretail.com</p>', 259),
