(216, 78, 19, '<p>brand idenity design</p>', '<p>hilde steen aamodt</p>', '<h1>falling in love</h1>\n<h2>with a brand.</h2>\n<p>Far too many people place an equals sign between the store experience and design. For us, design is a part of many things that must be defined when one creates a successful store concept. What primarily builds a concept – and hence the experience of a store, is the product line – how it is divided up and presented. The other dimension lies in how one affects and controls a gait pattern – by working with glance directions and rhythms in the room.</p>\n<p>We are of course equipped with many primal instincts, which serve mainly to identify sense-related similarities and differences in our surroundings. Sense perceptions such as light, smell and sound also belong to this dimension. All the elements contribute to dramatizing the customer''s perception of your shop and your brand name.</p>', '<p>Hilde Steen Aamodt, Senior Graphic Designer, has 20 years of experience in advertising and graphic design, the last 10 years with a focus on the development of brand identities. She has won the National Award for Design twice, and earned the reputation of being one of the most skilled graphic designers in Scandinavia.</p>', '<p>(+47) 900 39 019</p>', '<p>hilde@reactorretail.com</p>', 260),
(217, 51, 34, '<p>retail design</p>', '<p>stein erik berg</p>', '<h1>future is for the</h1>\n<h2>imaginative retailers</h2>\n<p>The perfect store, an artistic vision, the ultimate design, filled with dreams to inspire, incite and entertain. But a beautiful shopping experience is not enough. For a store to be successful, its retail design must express the soul of the brand - that is the brand´s values and strength. Striking the right balance between the products, communication, design, architecture and education is the only way to achieve this goal. As a retail designer, you need a unique mix of elements for each project, because every brand develops differently. The ultimate shopping experience is a place driven by passion and experience. You can have a fantastically designed store, but if the owners and staff aren´t  fully behind it, it will never work. Fantastic opportunities exist for imaginative retailers.</p>', '<p>Stein Berg is a highly skilled retail designer and store planner with more than 30 years of retail and concept development experience, and with hundred of thousands of square meters of retail space planned and behind the retail expression of brands as Stokke, IKEA, Oslo Airport, Moods of Norway and many more. </p>', '<p>(+47) 917 58 805</p>', '<p>seb@reactorretail.com</p>', 261),
(218, 83, 20, '<p>retail art direction</p>', '<p>ann-catrin friborg</p>', '<h1>a reason to visit</h1>\n<h2>and a reason to stay</h2>\n<p>Occasionally one feels welcome just by going into a room. At first, it is difficult to understand why. Then you understand that somebody has twisted and turned every detail and in so doing has created an integrated whole. The parts play together while they also each work individually to make the experience greater. A style is found here that you would like to experience over and over. It is design for your senses and a place where you want to spend time in, a place you want to come back to. We think that as a home reflects the personality of the owner, a store should also reflect the personality of your company and your brand. After all, for a retailer – the store is the brand itself. Your approach should thus be to create a holistic shopping experience that hopefully answers the most important question for anyone in retail: Why should somebody come to my store?</p>', '<p>Ann-Catrin Friborg, Retail Art Director, joined Reactor in 2003 after a 10-year international store design career with IKEA. She has led several major concept development projects and she is an expert in creating strong, differentiating and coherent retail experiences.</p>', '<p>(+47)  97 68 38 52 </p>', '<p>ancf@reactorretail.com</p>', 258),
(219, 52, 26, '<p>concept &amp; design direction</p>', '<p>øyvind nystad</p>', '<h1>natural instinct</h1>\n<h2>is king in store design</h2>\n<p>To us, design is just one of the dimensions needed to create a successful retail concept. The first dimension is of course the product line and how it is directed, segmented and presented to your customers. The second dimension is how interesting you can make the customer''s journey through your store, creating interesting sight lines and by changing the rhythm in different areas of the store. Why is all this important? As humans, we automatically try to understand and to navigate in a new environment. We use our natural instincts and all our senses to identify differences and to detect potential opportunities and dangers in our environment. Hence creating a sensory shopping experience that includes light, sound, shapes and scents helps to dramatise and build your customer''s perception of your store and your brand.</p>', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Øyvind Nystad, Creative Director and co-founder of Reactor. More than 25 years of concept development and design work for some of the world''s most respected brands has made Øyvind one of the most respected retail designers in Europe. </p>', '<p>(+47) 911 78 924</p>', '<p>oyvind@rectorretail.com</p>', 259),
