(243, 6, 78, '<p>brand &amp; concept strategies</p>', '<p>Dag Landewall</p>', '<h1>from vice to virtue</h1>\n<h2>a brand needs character</h2>\n<p>It''s not a coincidence that many of the world''s most successful brands have a founder with a strong personality that also becomes the company''s brand personality. IKEA is Ingvar Kamprad and Apple is (still) Steve Jobs. But that doesn''t mean companies without a charismatic founder cannot develop a strong, relevant and likeble character. Every single company has its own history with its unique traits, and ways of acting which add up to the company''s personality.</p>\n<p>I believe that a brand first of all should be authentic and true to its own culture. Instead of trying to become what you are not - be clear about what you really are. Identify and describe your virtues and define the consequences of being true to them. Do that and your brand gets authenticity and character. Then use it as a foundation for your concept development and design work.</p>', '<p>Dag Landewall, Senior Brand Strategist, is the co-founder of Reactor and has over 30 years of retail and concept development experience. He leads the company''s brand strategy work and creates compelling, consumer-relevant and to-the-point brand stories and personalities for select corporate clients.</p>', '<p>(+47) 952 12 345</p>', '<p><a href="mailto:dag@reactorretail.com">dag@reactorretail.com</a></p>', 257),
