(290, 51, 39, '<p>retail design</p>', '<p>stein erik berg</p>', '<h1>future is for the</h1>\n<h2>imaginative retailers</h2>\n<p>The perfect store, an artistic vision, the ultimate design, filled with dreams to inspire, incite and entertain. But a beautiful shopping experience is not enough. For a store to be successful, its retail design must express the soul of the brand - i.e. the brand´s values and strength. Striking the right balance between the products, communication, design, architecture and education is the only way to achieve this goal. As a retail designer, you need a unique mix of elements for each project, because every brand develops differently.</p>\n<p>The ultimate shopping experience is a place driven by passion and experience. You can have a fantastically designed store, but if the owners and staff are not fully behind it, it will never work. Fantastic opportunities exist for imaginative retailers.</p>', '<p>Stein Berg is a highly skilled retail designer and store planner with more than 30 years of retail and concept development experience, and with hundred of thousands of square meters of retail space planned and behind the retail experience of Stokke, IKEA, Oslo Airport, Moods of Norway and many more. </p>', '<p>(+47) 917 58 805</p>', '<p>seb@reactorretail.com</p>', 261),
(291, 80, 31, '<p>retail tender management &amp; roll-outs</p>', '<p>erik huseby</p>', '<h1>big ideas </h1>\n<h2>into the real world</h2>\n<p>In the disruptive and unpredictable market of today, many great ideas become irrelevant before they reach the marketplace. For many large companies it has proved difficult to adjust their concept development and implementation processes to this new reality.</p>\n<p>However, my experience is that it is possible to shorten the interval between the creation of the next big thing and its first encounter with real customers.</p>\n<p>Our approach is to prepare a concept for roll-out right from the start.  Also, concept elements should be prototyped as they are developed at the drawing table. Finally, a successful procurement process requires in-depth knowledge of the shop-fitting market and production methods. A professionally done retail tender management process normally accounts for 20 - 30% investment savings. Talk to me, and I will tell you how.</p>', '<p>Erik Huseby, Managing Director of Reactor Products, our implementation arm, leads our work with bringing the concepts we create into the real world, through sourcing, piloting and roll-out management. Erik has over 20 years of expertise in his field and is a leading shop-fitting authority and manages tender and hardware sourcing processes for a large number of our clients.   </p>', '<p>(+47) 916 86 244</p>', '<p>erik@reactorretail.com</p>', 264),
(292, 83, 21, '<p>retail art direction</p>', '<p>ann-catrin friborg</p>', '<h1>your best media</h1>\n<h2>is free. Do you use it? </h2>\n<p>You may not run one of largest store chains around but even medium sized retailers has millions of visitors and bypassers each year which makes the stores your most efficent media channel.  The best thing - you own it (that is, if you havn''t sold every shelv to the industry..). In addition to direct your customer through the store, you are able to influence your customers to act; by inspiration, knowledge and price. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Well managed, your stores becomes you own media channel and the driver of renewal and activity throughout the commercial calendar – they are living medias that are linked to external media and when you use them correctly they alone will be a reason for the customer to come back over and over again</p>', '<p>Ann-Catrin Friborg, Retail Art Director, joined Reactor in 2003 after a 10-year international store design career with IKEA. She has led several major concept development projects and she is an expert in creating strong, differentiating and coherent retail experiences.</p>', '<p>(+47)  97 68 38 52 </p>', '<p>ancf@reactorretail.com</p>', 258),
